title: Hundreds Killed And Missing As Cyclone Ditwah Triggers Deadly Flooding In Sri Lanka | 10 News
description: At least 159 people have been killed and around 200 remain missing after landslides and extreme flooding devastated Sri Lanka.  Cyclone Ditwah struck the South Asian island nation on Saturday, prompting troops to be deployed to rescue residents stranded by rising floodwaters.  Local officials reported that more than 20,000 homes were destroyed and over half a million people were affected nationwide, with more than 78,000 displaced to nearly 800 relief centres, most of them set up in schools.  The highest number of deaths was recorded in Kandy and Badulla, where many communities remain cut off. title: Ambulance Victoria drops 'no beards' requirement for paramedics | ABC NEWS
description: A student paramedic successfully challenged Ambulance Victoria's requirement that all ambulance workers be clean-shaven for mask fitting purposes.   19-year-old Prabhjeet Gill, who is Sikh, filed a complaint with the Australian Human Rights Commission, arguing that Ambulance Victoria's refusal to let him undertake a mask fitting without shaving first was discriminating on cultural and religious grounds.  The Singh Thattha mask fitting method involves covering the beard with an elastic band underneath the mask, and has been adopted in other jurisdictions to achieve a safe mask fitting. title: Airport chaos around the country as Jetstar grounds Airbus A320s | ABC NEWS
description: Thousands of Jetstar passengers across Australia have been affected by a global issue that has seen Airbus A320 planes around the world grounded.  Passengers flying with Jetstar have been told to expect major delays, and a number of flights were cancelled.  Jetstar has 86 of the A320 aircraft in its fleet of which 34 are affected by the software issue, while Qantas also uses the planes but said its services were not affected.  The flight disruptions in Australia were affecting all major domestic airports on Saturday morning, with multiple flight cancellations at all airports handling Jetstar flights. title: Sri Lanka Cyclone Ditwah Leaves Dozens Dead As Rescues Continue Amid Worsening Floods | 10 News
description: Cyclone Ditwah has swept across Sri Lanka, killing 46 people and leaving 23 missing as floods and landslides hit eastern and central regions after more than 300 millimetres of rain. Officials warn flooding is expected to worsen over the next 12 hours, including in parts of Colombo. Israeli authorities said the men were wanted for terror activity and have opened an investigation, but offered no explanation for why they were shot after appearing to surrender. title: Ken Henry welcomes deal to reform Australia's ageing environment laws | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: Former treasury secretary, Ken Henry, now chair of the Australian Climate and Biodiversity Foundation, has celebrated the deal between Labor and the Greens to reform Australia's environment laws. He has told The Business it "demonstrates the Australian parliament is up to the task of serious economic reform that promotes prosperity." Dr Henry says the reforms put an end to what he calls' the false dichotomy between the economy and the environment.' He says, "for centuries, humans have believed that economic and social progress necessarily comes at the expense of the environment." Labor's deal with the Greens will see more federal oversight of forestry and land clearing, and no "fast-tracking" for coal and gas projects. Ken Henry says "I don't see these as concessions, I see these as improvements." The deal comes five years after an independent review from Graeme Samuel called for similar environmental reform. #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Banking regulator to cap home loans amid housing boom | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: The banking regulator will impose new restrictions on home loans from early next year to limit the number of "high-risk" large loans being issued to customers. APRA is ordering the institutions under its supervision to limit high debt-to-income loans to 20 per cent of all new loans approved. The regulator says the 20 per cent cap will apply separately to investor and owner-occupier loans, to avoid the risk of investors "crowding out" owner-occupier buyers. A high debt-to-income loan is defined as one where the total amount borrowed is more than six times the borrower's annual household income. The new cap on high debt-to-income loans takes effect on February 1. Alicia Barry spoke with APRA chair, John Lonsdale, in his first TV interview. He says; "we're particularly targeting high debt to income lending, if we're successful at that, we'd expect good quality lending to keep happening through the economy and I think that's good for borrowers of all sorts."  #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE Read more here: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-11-27/banking-regulator-apra-imposes-home-loan-caps/106058604  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Rate hikes possible in 2026, warns CBA chief economist | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: Inflation accelerated more than expected in the year to October, according to new monthly figures. The measure the Reserve Bank looks closely at, the trimmed mean rose to 3.3 per cent, which is now higher than its target range. The RBA's target range is between 2-3 per cent. Headline inflation, at 3.8 per cent came in higher than market expectations, 3.6 per cent. Some economists think the easing cycle over, while others are warning of volatility in the data.  Commonwealth Bank's chief economist Luke Yeaman is warning that Australia's economy is running close to full speed, creating a headache for the Reserve Bank.  He says stronger growth, a resilient labour market, rising house prices and an inflation surprise in the September quarter and October monthly quarters have taken rate cuts off the table and raised the risk of hikes in 2026.  He thinks Australia is "getting close to our economic speed limit", with potential growth now lower.   Speaking to ABC TV's The Business, Mr Yeaman said "the question is where to from here into 2026? Do they (the RBA) need to take out a little bit more insurance to keep inflation under control?"  "Our view is that when you look through the inflation surprises that we've had some of those factors driving that are temporary, and some of them look a little more persistent, but there are definitely some temporary factors at play too. So we're still hopeful that as we move into 2026, we'll start to see the economy stabilise and inflation come back towards the target band. But there are certainly risks mounting on the upside."  Even though energy prices have rose on an annual basis by 37 per cent to October, Mr Yeaman says while it impacts households, the Reserve Bank isn't concerned about energy prices, they're "looking through it". #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: 9News Melbourne | Wednesday November 26 | Full Bulletin
description: Alicia Loxley and Tom Steinfort present the Melbourne news, covering the renewed police search for missing mother Samantha Murphy in Enfield State Park following new intelligence. We also bring you an update from the Supreme Court on the historic Easey Street murders case, where the accused has been committed to stand trial for two murder charges.  The biggest headlines include an inflation shock with prices rising faster than expected, fueling fears of a Christmas interest rate hike. In city news, the Metro Tunnel faces controversy over a potential pedestrian toll between stations, leading to a late government backflip. Plus, Victoria Police has been granted unprecedented powers to conduct random, warrantless searches across the CBD to combat knife crime, a move that has drawn strong criticism from civil liberties groups.  We also cover an Optus outage, a serious machete attack in Broadmeadows, an AFL Brownlow betting scandal update, and a look at the spectacular new Formula 1 Exhibition making its Australian debut in Melbourne. description: German pastor Henrik Lenkeit was shocked to discover his grandfather was top Nazi politician Heinrich Himmler through a World War II documentary. Under the best case scenario, Perth would see the most price growth, up to 14%, while Adelaide and Brisbane are at a 12% projection. title: BHP's mining operations in SA outback use 33m litres of water a day | ABC NEWS
description: Arabana elders from the north of South Australia are calling on mining giant BHP to cease water extraction from the Great Artesian Basin, where many culturally significant local mound springs have been damaged or have dried up, affecting local ecosystems.  BHP currently extracts more than 33 million litres of water per day from the basin for its Olympic Dam operations, but says it acknowledges the cultural significance of the mound springs and the Great Artesian Basin to the Arabana people, and that it regularly engages with traditional owners.  The SA government is proposing to build a major desalination plant in the Upper Spencer Gulf, which would provide water to BHP and other industries. Environmentalists are calling for water extraction to end once the desalination plant is operational.   Original reporting by Leah MacLennan for ABC News SA. Social version by Madeleine Wales. title: Trump to take on Somali Gangs in Minnesota with savage warning to Tim Walz
description: US President Donald Trump has announced a move to end temporary protected status for Somalis in Minnesota. title: Severe Tropical Cyclone Fina leaves a path of destruction in her wake | ABC NEWS
description: 00:00 Severe Tropical Cyclone Fina has passed Darwin and the Tiwi Islands at category three strength, with the weather system's gale-force winds leaving a path of destruction as it continues west into the ocean. Fina was the Northern Territory's strongest cyclone to pass Darwin since the deadly Cyclone Tracy in 1974. The system was also more powerful than Cyclone Marcus, which passed Darwin as a category two in 2018. Now tracking west-south-west, Severe TC Fina is picking up strength over the Timor Sea and is expected to move over the top of Western Australia in the coming days. 02:11 ABC reporter Olivana Lathouris on trying to get a sense of when things will return to normal. 03:12 Despite the massive clean-up ahead for Darwin, the city's resilience has shone through as locals pick up the pieces ready to move on. 05:20 With power still down across parts of Darwin, Power and Water crews are working to restore as many homes as possible.  08:22 ABC meteorologist Nate Byrne on experiencing his first cyclone, and Fina's path from here. title: Tropical Cyclone Fina Batters Northern Territory | 10 News
description: Tropical Cyclone Fina has brought destructive winds and heavy rainfall, causing widespread damage across the Northern Territory capital.   The category 3 cyclone hit Darwin on Saturday, leaving more than 19,000 homes and businesses without power in the past 24 hours.  Darwin Airport was forced to close for 24 hours, only reopening this morning, and schools in Darwin are assessing whether it is safe for students to return tomorrow.  The Bureau of Meteorology says gusts of more than 200 km/h are possible, with the Northern Territory and parts of Western Australia still experiencing dangerous conditions as the system shifts away from the coast.  Authorities say communities should remain alert, as Cyclone Fina continues to evolve and warn it may bring further severe weather in the coming days. title: Donald Trump showers praise on Zohran Mamdani | ABC NEWS
description: Donald Trump has showered praise on New York's mayor-elect, Zohran Mamdani, during a warm and friendly press conference where they pledged to work together to lower living costs in America's biggest city. The US president and the democratic socialist had spent months trading pointed barbs, but presented a united front after meeting at the White House, even as reporters asked about their past attacks on each other. "We just had a great meeting. I think you're going to have, hopefully, a really great mayor. He has views that are a little out there, but who knows? title: Leavitt clashes with reporter over Ukraine-Russia peace plan
description: White House Press Secretary Karoline Leavitt has sparred with a reporter over claims the Trump administration's Ukraine peace plan demands major concessions from Kyiv.  During Thursday's press briefing, a reporter pressed Leavitt on whether Russia had been involved in drafting the proposal, saying sources described the plan as requiring "major concessions from Ukraine" and "not much from Russia".  Leavitt rejected that outright.  "Your understanding is wrong. Have you read the full plan? You haven't," she snapped back.  "You've read reporting from one side of the war."  She insisted the administration has spoken "equally with both sides," adding that President Trump, his national security team, envoy Elliot Witkoff and Secretary Marco Rubio have all engaged directly with both Kyiv and Moscow.  Leavitt said Witkoff and Rubio met Ukrainian officials again in the past week to discuss the proposal, which she called "a good plan for both Russia and Ukraine."  The clash came as two people familiar with the talks told reporters the US has signalled to President Zelenskyy that Ukraine may have to give up territory and surrender some weapons as part of the draft framework.  They requested anonymity due to the sensitivity of the discussions.

description: For the past two years Mrs Reading's family has used one of the coloured sand products, which were recalled last week due to potential asbestos contamination, for their rangoli artworks to celebrate the Hindu Diwali festival. title: Indonesia‚Äôs Mount Semeru Eruption Prompts Travel Warning & Evacuations | 10 News
description: Indonesia‚Äôs Mount Semeru, the tallest peak on Java Island, has erupted, prompting evacuations and leading authorities to raise the alert to the highest level.  Ash clouds as high as 2 kilometres high were seen spewing above the mountain's peak and a mixture of rock, lava and gas travelled up to 7km down its slopes several times from midday to dusk.  More than 300 residents in the three villages most at risk in the district of Lumajang were evacuated to government shelters, but no casualties have been reported.  The Australian Bureau of Meteorology's Volcanic Ash Advisory Centre has issued a red aviation alert following the eruption. title: Man Steals Car With Baby Inside | 10 News
description: Police are searching for a man who stole a vehicle before realising there was a baby in the backseat.  A sleeping child was inside a car in a supermarket carpark in Shepparton, Victoria while the victim quickly ran into the store at about 2pm on November 14.  An unknown male then stole the red Volkswagen and reversed it out of the carpark, before realising there was a baby in the backseat.  The man then took the baby out of the car and placed it in a nearby box, the child was located immediately after the victim returned.  The stolen car was located on November 15 in the Mooroopna area, with police releasing CCTV of the incident in the hope the public will be able to assist them in their investigation.  Police describe the man as being aged in his 20s to 30s, a slim build, 165cm tall, wearing a black cap backwards, navy headphones, a blue Golden State basketball singlet, black shorts, light blue runners and black sweatbands on both wrists. title: House prices and rents to keep rising in 2026, says Domain | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: A gradual rise in household incomes is one reason why house prices are expected to reach record highs in all capital cities by the end of next year.  That's according to Domain's forecast report for 2026. It shows house prices will rise by 6 per cent across the capitals, compared to 9 per cent this year.  Units will go up by 5 per cent, in a market that's expected to be more balanced and policy-driven. Domain's chief of research and economics Nicola Powell says the forecast for growth is largely due to the expansion of the first home guarantee scheme. She says the first half of next year will likely see first home buyers competing with investors, but as capital growth starts to slow, investors will likely pull back. Domain's report reveals the biggest increase in house prices will be seen in the most rate-sensitive cities of Sydney and Melbourne.  Nicola Powell says Sydney's median house price is expected to hit $1.9 million in 2026, and setting a pathway for a $2 million median house price in Sydney by 2027. Rental price growth is also forecast across all capital cities, however Nicola Powell says she would describe the projects as modest and in line with inflation. "We're expecting a little bit of an uptick in the rate of rental price growth in Sydney and Melbourne for house rents, but in most of our capital cities, we're expecting unit rents to grow faster than house rents", she says. "That really is this steer towards more affordable rental properties, smaller rental properties because we know the rental market has been extremely strained over recent years." #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Cyclone Fina reaches category two strength, expected to cross NT coast on Saturday | ABC NEWS
description: Tropical Cyclone Fina is sitting more than 350 kilometres north-east of Darwin, and has now intensified into a category two.   Fina is tracking north-east away from the Northern Territory, but the weather bureau expects the system to change course and begin moving towards the NT coastline. The storm's path remains uncertain, but forecasters are predicting the system will make landfall at the Cobourg Peninsula, and potentially impact Darwin.  A cyclone watch is currently in place between the Tiwi Islands east to Millingimbi but the watch area will likely be extended.  The weather bureau is warning of destructive wind gusts up to 135 kilometres an hour across the northern coastline as the storm approaches. NT emergency service advises to not panic and have your cyclone kits prepared.   Jack Hislop has this update for ABC News Northern Territory. title: Why workers could see their real wages go backwards in 2026 | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: Wage growth slightly outpaces consumer price inflation in the year to September, which means the average worker has received a small increase in their purchasing power, a point highlighted by the Treasurer Jim Chalmers.  However, the increase was down on the same period last year and an economist says workers can expect real wages to fall again next year. Wage rises were stronger for workers in the public sector, led by pay rises for employees of state and local governments. The data alleviates any pressure on the Reserve Bank to lower interest rates.  William Buck chief economist Besa Deda thinks there's a possibility of one more cut in the second half of 2026.  The ABS published a second set of monthly numbers, estimating the total wages and salaries paid by employers to their staff in September.  Payments totalled $108.8 billion, driven higher by bonuses in the mining, utilities, retail, media and financial services sectors, which are often paid in September, in response to financial year targets.  However, the 5.3 per cent annual growth in total wages and salaries paid to employees was down from the 6.1 per cent rise recorded over the year to September 2024. #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE Read more here: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-11-19/abs-wage-price-index-figures-released-september-quarter/106026360  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: US Lawmakers Vote To Release Epstein files In Huge Majority | 10 News
description: The U.S. House has passed legislation on Tuesday, November 18, to force the Justice Department to release the Epstein files, after a final vote of 427-1.  Prior to the vote, Speaker Mike Johnson said that the Republican Party has "always" supported "maximum transparency" but urged caution, if releasing files, not to violate victim privacy or disclose names of whistleblowers.  President Donald Trump had previously dismissed efforts to release the files, repeatedly referring to it as a "distraction" and a "Democratic hoax", before urging House Republicans to vote in favour of the release two days ago. title: Calls to change ASX trading rules after DroneShield share crash | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: After running a dizzying rally this year, DroneShield saw its stock plunge by more than 30 per cent in a day on November 13.  The sell-off came after the news the chief executive Oleg Vornik, chair Peter James and director Jethro Marks offloaded all of their shares in the counter drone technology company.  The company announced the share sales on November 12 after a previous announcement on November 5, that Oleg Vornik, Peter James and Jethro Marks had received performance share options, triggered by the company achieving milestone of $200 million in cash receipts over a 12-month rolling period. They converted the majority of their performance options to ordinary shares, then sold them between November 6 and November 12. Experts say sales like this can affect investor confidence. International corporate governance and sustainability expert Thomas Clarke says there are no rules against it but he thinks there "should be a window to prevent directors selling out the bulk of their shares or a very large proportion of their shares so soon after an announcement."  Investors also are calling for changes to regulations.   DroneShield told the market, the share sales by the CEO and others were unrelated to the growth trajectory of the company, which it said remains strong, as highlighted in the recent quarterly market update. Directors also retain a stake in the company through vested options, but CEO Oleg Vornik holds less than 200,000 vested share options out of the 15 million he was awarded.  DroneShield shares have surged more than 200 per cent this year.  The share price picked up 12 per cent on Monday. title: Cattle, Water, and Power: Life on the Macquarie Marshes | Landline | ABC News
description: The Macquarie Marshes in New South Wales is an internationally recognised wetland system that's a vital breeding site for waterbirds. It's also been home to graziers for generations. Irrigators and regional towns rely on the river that feeds the marshlands as well. But Landline's Kerry Staight found there are questions about whether enough water is getting through to the fragile landscape.  Landline is a national rural affairs television program covering stories from rural and regional Australia. title: Croc owners welcome government crackdown on Territorian‚Äôs best friend | ABC NEWS
description: Under the Northern Territory government's proposed new crocodile ownership rules, pet owners would be charged a $299 permit fee for the privilege. If the plan goes ahead, croc owners would also face $300 fines if their pets escape, plus another $100 for each hour the reptile remains on the loose. Attorney-General Marie-Clare Boothby said the government wanted to "ensure there is responsible crocodile ownership" in the NT, where 63 residents are currently licensed to own pet crocs. The plan also includes a requirement for new owners to have their animals undergo a procedure to receive identification markings, as well as upgrades to enclosure standards. By Matt Garrick for ABC News Northern Territory. The flooding followed nearly 12 centimetres of rainfall in south-east Wales overnight, causing the River Monnow to rise to a record level and spill over its banks.  Natural Resources Wales issued several flood warnings for Monmouth and the surrounding areas, citing an ongoing ‚Äúsignificant risk to life and significant disruption to the community.‚Äù  Emergency rescue crews worked to evacuate and assist residents of the town. title: AFP charge three people over alleged $71 million Defence contracts fraud | ABC NEWS
description: Three Northern Territory residents have been arrested and charged with fraud, and one of them also with corruption over an alleged multi-million-dollar Defence contract scheme. Australian Federal Police (AFP) investigators raided homes and businesses across Darwin on Friday after receiving a tip-off from the Department of Defence about the alleged crime. The AFP alleges a 48-year-old Commonwealth Defence employee, his 40-year-old wife, and a 41-year-old male director of a local construction firm had conspired to channel nearly $71 million of Defence building contracts to their own company. During the raids, investigators seized $30,000 in cash, documents, electronic devices, jewellery and a small quantity of illicit drugs, which the AFP suspects is cocaine. In a statement, the AFP alleged that the group "were involved in a conspiracy to influence the awarding of tenders to their company, with the intention of dishonestly gaining a benefit from the Commonwealth, namely the Department of Defence". By Felicity James for ABC News Northern Territory. title: Blue Origin launches rocket carrying NASA spacecraft to Mars | ABC NEWS
description: Blue Origin has successfully launched its biggest rocket with a pair of NASA spacecraft destined for Mars.  The 98-metre New Glenn blasted into the sky from Cape Canaveral Space Force Station on Thursday afternoon, local time, sending twin Mars orbiters on a journey to the Red Planet.  The launch followed several days of delays due to cloudy skies and a geomagnetic storm.  The space venture of billionaire Amazon founder Jeff Bezos achieved a key engineering objective when its reusable first-stage booster separated from the rocket's upper stage minutes after launch and flew back to Earth.  The New Glenn is carrying two satellites on their way to Mars in the company's first NASA-scale science mission.  The dual spacecraft, dubbed Blue and Gold, are due to reach Mars in 2027. title: Dumping net zero will spook investors says economist, Orica says it's disruptive | The Business
description: The Liberal Party has announced it will scrap its net zero by 2050 commitment as part of its energy and climate policy. Opposition Leader Susan Ley says the party can deliver lower power prices and reduced emissions without the target. The announcement has been met with silence and in some cases, open dismay. Businesses say when it comes to Australia's climate commitments, they've been consistent in asking for policy certainty. Director of Green Energy Markets Tristan Edis says the announcement would make some international investors nervous. "Before this announcement I think investors could at least reassure themselves that if they make the investments, they can at least say, 'you've made a promise you need to deliver on it'", he says. "But now I think there would be a great degree of nervousness about that". Orica CEO Sanjeev Gandhi says the change is disruptive and "we do not want to end up decimating manufacturing in Australia." #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Conservationist Jane Goodall Honoured At Washington Funeral By Friends And Family | 10 News
description: Jane Goodall has been farewelled at Washington National Cathedral, honoured as a visionary scientist whose work reshaped primatology and inspired global conservation efforts.   Hundreds gathered, including Leonardo DiCaprio, Nancy Pelosi and Dr Francis Collins, sharing memories of her unwavering belief that hope and compassion could drive change.   Goodall, who died aged 91 while on a speaking tour, was celebrated for her groundbreaking chimpanzee research and decades of environmental advocacy through the Jane Goodall Institute and Roots & Shoots.   Mourners reflected on her gentle authority, humour and enduring message that every person can help heal the planet. title: Indigenous protesters storm UN climate summit in Brazil | ABC NEWS
description: Dozens of Indigenous protesters forced their way into the COP30 climate summit venue and clashed with security guards at the entrance to demand climate action and forest protection.  Protesters demanded access to the UN compound where thousands of delegates from countries around the world are attending this year's UN climate summit in the Amazon city of Belem, Brazil.  Some waved flags with slogans calling for land rights or carried signs saying, "Our land is not for sale."  Security guards pushed the protesters back and used tables to barricade the entrance. A Reuters witness saw one security guard being rushed away in a wheelchair while clutching his stomach.  Another guard with a fresh cut above his eye told Reuters he had been hit in the head by a heavy drumstick thrown from the crowd. Security confiscated several long, heavy sticks.  The protesters dispersed shortly after the clash. They had been in a group of hundreds who marched to the venue.  Security guards later allowed delegates to exit the venue, having earlier asked them to move back inside until the area was clear. Within the compound, the United Nations is responsible for security.  "Earlier this evening, a group of protesters breached security barriers at the main entrance to the COP, causing minor injuries to two security staff, and minor damage to the venue," a spokesperson said in a statement.  "Brazilian and UN security personnel took protective actions to secure the venue, following all established security protocols. Brazilian and UN authorities are investigating the incident. The venue is fully secured, and COP negotiations continue."  Brazilian President Luiz In√°cio Lula da Silva has highlighted Indigenous communities as key players in this year's COP30 negotiations. title: Sydney honours fallen on Remembrance Day | 7NEWS
description: Remembrance Day services across Sydney marked the 107th anniversary of the Armistice, honouring all Australians killed in conflict from World War I to Afghanistan. title: Shoppers prepare to spend billions on Black Friday deals | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: It is shaping up to be the biggest retail event of the year with shoppers already hunting for Black Friday deals. Australians are expected to spend a record $6.8 billion over the Black Friday‚ÄìCyber Monday weekend, according to research from the Australian Retailers Association (ARA) in partnership with Roy Morgan. That's a 4 per cent increase on last year. Overall, about 6 million Australians are expected to take part in Black Friday sales this year. On average, they will fork out $804 each. Recent interest rate cuts have delivered a greater sense of optimism. Research from Westpac and the Melbourne Institute shows consumer sentiment surged in November by almost 13 per cent. It's the first time that optimists have outnumbered pessimists in years. Other data from Shopify shows more Australians are using artificial intelligence to help guide purchases. title: Scientists found a giant spider city in a cave | ABC NEWS
description: If the words 'arachnid supercity' set your pulse racing ... maybe sit this one out. In Sulfur Cave, straddling the Greek‚ÄìAlbanian border, lies what could be the largest spider web ever found, a recent study has revealed. After first discovering the colonial spider community in 2022, researchers now estimate the more than 100-square-metre web is home to around 110,000 spiders. Two different species inhabit the web, each genetically distinct from their relatives on the surface.  The researchers also say it's the first time these usually solitary spiders have been seen forming colonies, a finding the team describes as "extraordinary." It's thought the reason for the Sulfur Cave's popularity with spiders is the huge number of midges that also dwell in its depths, offering a plentiful food source for the arachnids. title: Trump threatens to sue the BBC for $1 billion over 'false and defamatory' documentary clip
description: US President Donald Trump threatened to sue the BBC for $1US billion.  The threat relates to a BBC Panorama documentary about Trump's January 6, 2021, speech, which has faced widespread criticism.  During the documentary, there was a doctored recording of a speech he gave before the January 6 Capitol Hill riots, which quoted the president out of context.  In a letter sent to the BBC from Trump's legal team, they called on the company to retract the "false, defamatory, disparaging, and inflammatory statements" immediately.  The BBC Chair, Samir Shah, has since apologised for an "error of judgment" made within the documentary.  Following The Telegraph breaking the story, the BBC director general Tim Davie and the CEO of News Deborah Turness both resigned.

The biggest typhoon to threaten the Philippines in years, Fung-wong could cover two-thirds of the archipelago with its 1800km-wide rain and wind band, forecasters said. #typhoon #supertyphoon #wildweather #bridge #Philippines

description: At least two people have died, and one million people evacuated as Super Typhoon Fung-wong made landfall in the Philippines on Sunday.  Videos posted on social media show the deadly storm battering the nation with winds of up to 230kmph, torrential rain, and dangerous storm surges.  Authorities said the storm, known locally as Uwan, is expected to head towards Taiwan.  It was the 21st storm this year to hit the country and comes less than a week after Typhoon Kalmaegi left more than 200 people dead. title: Three Dead After Wild Seas Smash Island of Tenerife | 10 News
description: Three people have died and a further 15 were injured after the popular Spanish holiday island of Tenerife was battered by rough seas.  One man reportedly fell into the water north of the island, and was airlifted to hospital where he was subsequently pronounced dead.  Elsewhere, a man was pronounced dead after being found floating in the water south of the island, and a woman reportedly suffered a fatal heart attack after being swept into the ocean along with 10 other people at Puerto de la Cruz.  Local officials have warned tourists and residents alike to stay away from coastal paths and to not take pictures or videos of the wild swells. Turbulent weather in the region is expected to worsen over the coming days. title: Toyah's Murder: What we know so far | ABC NEWS
description: You can't spend too long in Far North Queensland without spotting a bumper sticker bearing the name "Toyah". In this episode, ABC Far North Queensland reporter Christopher Testa and Stephen Stockwell talk through what we know about the case so far, as jury selection begins.   If you have any questions about this trial you'd like Chris and Stocky to answer in future episodes, please email thecaseof@abc.net.au (mailto:thecaseof@abc.net.au) .   The Case Of is the follow-up to the hit podcast Mushroom Case Daily, and all episodes of that show will remain available in the back catalogue of The Case Of.

title: Typhoon Kalmaegi Batters Vietnam After Killing Nearly 200 In The Philippines | 10 News
description: Typhoon Kalmaegi has left a trail of devastation across the Philippines and Vietnam, killing at least 193 people and leaving more than a hundred missing.  The storm tore through central Vietnam with winds of up to 149km/h, uprooting trees, ripping roofs from homes and forcing mass evacuations as hundreds of thousands sought shelter. title: Deadly typhoon Kalmagi strikes Vietnam after Philippines devastation | 7NEWS
description: Typhoon Kalmagi, the deadliest typhoon of the year, has made landfall in Vietnam after devastating the Philippines and killing at least 114 people. description: Intense fighting is continuing in and around the city of Pokrovsk in eastern Ukraine's Donetsk region, with Moscow deploying around 100,000 troops into battle in a bid to capture the strategic centre. title: Scientists hopeful they have found source of SA algal bloom toxins | ABC NEWS
description: Scientists believe they may have identified a little-known algal species called Karenia cristata as the source of the brevetoxins within South Australia's devastating algal bloom. The breakthrough research, which is undergoing academic peer review, also shows it to have been the dominant species for the majority of the bloom's existence and one of five Karenia species present. Karenia cristata is the only one known to produce the algal toxins within the bloom. title: Building up, not out is key to solving housing supply crisis, says Grattan Institute | The Business
description: Australia needs around 250,000 new homes to be built a year over the next four years to reach the 1.2 million home government target. 176,000 homes were built in the first year of the National Housing Accord. Builders and experts agree building out isn't enough. Now the prominent think-tank The Grattan Institute says building up is part of the solution. Housing and economic security programme director at the Grattan Institute, Brendan Coates says Australian cities are some of the least dense of their size in the world. "We haven't allowed enough housing in those areas where Australians most want to live in those inner and middle ring suburbs of our capital cities," he says. Grattan wants a green light for three story dwellings on every residential block, adding 67,000 new homes a year and saving $100,000 a house. However the building industry says there's a drastic short fall of skilled labour. Supervisor at McDonald Jones Homes, Brian Skinner says "Skilled labour is still the number one issue that the building industry, not only in New South Wales but across Australia, needs to tackle." Land prices have also been flagged as a barrier to building more homes. #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: UK humiliated after accidentally releasing second migrant sex offender from prison
description: A second migrant sex offender has been released from prison, only weeks after another migrant sex offender was mistakenly released.  According to The Telegraph, the 24-year-old sex offender Ibrahim Kaddour-Cherif was released from South London prison, HMP Wandsworth, last week.  Despite Kaddour-Cherif‚Äôs release occurring last week, the Metropolitan Police were not informed until this Tuesday.  The Telegraph reports the 24-year-old was serving time for trespass with the intent to steal, but previously committed a sexual offence of indecent exposure.  The release of the Algerian migrant came less than two weeks after the release of Epping sex offender, Hadush Kebatu, from HMP Chelmsford.  According to The Telegraph, Kebatu was to be transferred to an immigration removal centre but was instead released, resulting in a 2-day manhunt.

title: Kentucky Plane Crash Death Toll Updated, Black Box Found | 10 News
description: The death toll of the fiery UPS cargo plane crash in Louisville, Kentucky has been updated to at least nine people.  While only three were onboard the flight which was departing to Honolulu, six others have been confirmed dead, with 11 more injured.  Authorities expect the number of fatalities to rise.  The National Transport Safety Board advise that the plane's left wing caught fire and its engine fell off, just before it crashed and exploded after taking off.  They have also confirmed the aircraft's cockpit voice recorder and the flight data recorder, commonly known as the black box, has been found. title: World Reacts As Former US Vice-President Dick Cheney Dies Aged 84 | 10 News
description: Former US vice-president Dick Cheney, one of the most powerful and controversial figures in modern American politics, has died aged 84 from complications of pneumonia and cardiovascular disease. title: Why any rate relief for borrowers is now well into next year | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: A Melbourne Cup rate cut from the Reserve Bank was a non-starter. After three cuts this year, the RBA board kept the cash rate on hold at 3.6 per cent with its Governor Michele Bullock citing hotter-than-expected inflation. The RBA now says it's on the fence when it comes to its next interest rate move.  But some economists say any rate relief for borrowers won't happen until at least the middle of 2026. Economist Chris Richardson says "the last mile in the fight against inflation is pretty tough" for most central banks. Cost of living pressures are being driven by surging electricity prices and housing, with property prices rising at the fastest pace in more than two years. For borrowers, Canstar's Sally Tindall says there's been a surge in refinancing -- with roughly a thousand borrowers switching lenders each day. Ms Tindall says the average owner occupier's variable is around 5.5 per cent, but a competitive rate would be below 5.25 per cent. #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Is the government's plan to give free power not as good as it seems? | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: From July next year, households will have access to at least three free hours of power as long as they take up the default market offer and have a smart meter. The government's newly announced Solar Sharer Scheme will force retailers to make it available to consumers in NSW, South East Queensland, and South Australia. The aim is to soak up the nation's abundant daytime solar power, stabilising the grid and lowering power prices in peak periods. The founder of SolarQuotes, now owned by Origin Energy, Finn Peacock says its a great headline, but the devil is in the detail. " I think its a good idea to reduce the cost of electricity during the day, to encourage more electricity during the day, but I think forcing retailers to offer it for free for three hours is only likely to push up other costs for consumers." Power retailers say they've been blindsided and shocked by the scheme that puts smaller operators under pressure. Chief Executive Officer at the Australian Energy Council says "Generally the charge that comes from the companies that operate the poles are wires still exists for that middle of the day but retailers are effectively covering that cost in the middle of the day." she says " For smaller retailers in particular we do need to think carefully about whether they can actually cover those costs. "   #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: Four Nations Conduct Military Drills in Disputed South China Sea | 10 News
description: The Philippines, United States, Australia, and New Zealand have conducted naval and air drills in the disputed South China Sea in recent days.  Videos released by the Armed Forces of the Philippines on Saturday show the exercises took place from Thursday to Friday, involving forces from all four nations.  This marks the 12th such joint military drill the Philippines has staged with allied countries since last year, aimed at protecting its sovereign rights in the contested waters.  Philippine military spokesperson Col. title: Teens Arrested Following Clash With D.C. Police On Halloween | 10 News
description: At least five teenagers were arrested after a violent clash with D.C.‚Äôs Metropolitan Police Department (MPD) on Friday night.  According to the Metropolitan Police Department, the arrests were made for ‚Äúdisorderly behaviour‚Äù on Halloween evening, with additional arrests carried out by Metro Transit Police.  Police reported that a crowd of about 700 people had gathered around 8pm, in a park area near downtown‚Äôs Navy Yard Metro station. The group began to block traffic, engage in multiple fights, and ignore orders to remain on the sidewalks.  MPD said five males between the ages of 14 and 18 were arrested on charges ranging from possession of a knife to failure to obey and resisting arrest. Metro Transit Police made additional arrests.  One officer was injured during the clash and treated by emergency services at the scene.  The crowd was finally dispersed around 11pm. title: Sudan Horror, Witnesses Report Mass Executions After Al-Fashir Falls | 10 News
description: Hundreds of unarmed men have reportedly been executed near Sudan‚Äôs city of al-Fashir after Rapid Support Forces (RSF) seized the last army stronghold in Darfur following an 18-month siege.  Survivors who escaped to Tawila say fighters rounded up civilians, separated men from women and shot detainees after hurling racial slurs, with satellite analysis suggesting systematic ethnic-based killings.  Reuters and UN-verified videos show RSF fighters shooting captives and bodies scattered across streets, despite RSF denials and claims of ‚Äúmedia exaggeration‚Äù. title: US Ambassador interrupted by Cuba at UN | ABC NEWS
description: US Ambassador to the UN Mike Waltz was interrupted during a speech at the United Nations General Assembly by the Foreign Minister of Cuba, Bruno Rodriguez.   The General Assembly were due to vote on whether to condemn the United States' economic restrictions on Cuba.   "Mr Waltz, this is the United Nations General Assembly," Mr Rodriguez said. "It's not a Signal chat. Nor is it the House of Representatives."   He also said Mr Waltz was speaking in an "uncivilised, crude and gross way".  But Mr Waltz's speech was unable to convince many countries, with the UN General Assembly voting 165-7, with 12 abstentions to condemn the US economic embargo against Cuba. title: ACT closes 'legal loophole' making institutions more liable for child sexual abuse | ABC NEWS
description: The ACT has become the first jurisdiction to pass legislation expanding the liability of churches, sporting groups and other organisations to include the actions of paedophiles. A Canberra survivor of child sexual abuse and their lawyer have welcomed the legislation. description: U.S. President Donald Trump said his nation would resume nuclear weapons testing for the first time in 33 years. title: New AFP taskforce to target men 'hunting' young girls for violent acts | ABC NEWS
description: The Australian Federal Police have been working with Microsoft to develop AI tools to interpret Gen Z and Alpha slang to quickly identify children at risk of sadistic online exploitation.  New AFP Commissioner Krissy Barrett used her first speech at the National Press Club on Wednesday to announce the creation of Taskforce Pompilid, which will use the technology amongst a raft of measures to crack down on decentralised online crime networks.    The AFP is warning that young girls are being "hunted, stalked and drawn-in" by men using online networks to coerce them into carrying out serious acts of violence on themselves, their siblings or pets, in a "twisted type of gamification".  The Commissioner also offered practical steps to keep children out of harm's way.  "Let kids know they have the right to feel safe online and, if something feels uncomfortable, they can leave a chat at any time and tell a safe adult.   You can encourage safe conversations by talking regularly about online activities and apps, encouraging critical thinking, and reassuring kids that they won't be punished for coming forward if they think they have done something wrong.   Also, you can look out for warning signs that include self-harm, changes in eating or sleeping habits, sudden withdrawal from friends, families or activities, use of extreme behaviour, extreme language or symbols, and rejection of previously held morals.   Importantly, there are really practical and easy resources available, including how to make a report about child exploitation, at the AFP-led Australian Centre to Counter Child Exploitation website. That's www.acce.gov.au". she said.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: No rate cut until mid-2026, says NAB chief economist | The Business | ABC NEWS
description: Inflation has surged in the September quarter with consumer prices rising at an annual pace of 3.2 per cent, up from 2.1 per cent in the June quarter. The "trimmed mean" for the September quarter, which strips out the most volatile price moves up and down, came in at 1 per cent. The headline number was 1.3 per cent. On an annual basis, the trimmed mean lifted to the top of the RBA's target band at 3 per cent. It was much hotter than the RBA and market economists were expecting, squashing hopes of a rate cut next week. In fact, NAB chief economist Sally Auld told The Business NAB isn't expecting another rate cut until mid-2026. "No rate cuts for the rest of this year, likely no rate cuts in the first quarter of next year, but we do have one more rate cut in our profile but not until May of 2026," She said. "I think really the message from today's numbers is that it is going to require a little bit of patience on the part of mortgage holders just to give the Reserve Bank a good chance to get comfortable and a bit more confident in terms of some of the underlying drivers of inflation."  #ABCBusiness Subscribe: http://ab.co/1svxLVE Read more here: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-10-29/september-quarter-inflation-kills-interest-rate-cut/105946770  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. title: King Charles heckled over brother Prince Andrew | ABC NEWS
description: King Charles was heckled by a protester on Monday over his brother Prince Andrew's ties to the late sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. The king was greeting royal fans during a cathedral visit in Britain.  "How long have you known about Andrew and Epstein?," the man could be heard shouting outside Lichfield Cathedral in northwest England, close to Birmingham.  Although Prince Andrew, 65, said this month that he would give up using his title of Duke of York after years of scrutiny over his behaviour and connections to Epstein, questions about him ‚Äî and what the royals knew of events ‚Äî have intensified since.  The contents of a posthumous memoir by Virginia Giuffre, who accused the prince of sexually abusing her as a teenager, have triggered renewed backlash over the issue this month.  Andrew has always denied Giuffre's account. In 2022, he made an undisclosed payment to settle a lawsuit brought in the US by Giuffre, who died by suicide in April.  British police are looking into media reports that in 2011 Andrew had asked one of his police officers to dig up dirt on Giuffre.  The protester could also be heard saying: "Have you asked the police to cover up for Andrew? ... Should the MPs (members of parliament) be allowed to debate the royals in the House of Commons?"  The monarch ignored the protester and carried on engaging with other members of the public.  ABC NEWS provides around the clock coverage of news events as they break in Australia and abroad. The remarks were Trump's latest on the subject, which he has teased in public remarks and with "Trump 2028" hats he hands out at the White House. No one may be elected to the US presidency a third time, according to the 22nd Amendment of the US Constitution. Some have suggested that one way around this prohibition would be for Trump to stand as vice president, while another candidate stood for president and resigned, letting Trump again assume the presidency. Opponents have disputed whether this would be legal. Referring to Vice President JD Vance and Secretary of State Marco Rubio, Trump also said they were "great people" who could run for the office. title: Trump Again Refuses To Rule Out Third Presidential Run | 10 News
description: US President Donald Trump has once again refused to categorically rule out attempting to run for a third presidential term, further stoking rising fears he may try to subvert the US constitution.  The constitution's 22nd amendment prevents anyone from being elected to the office of president more than twice. However, this hasn't stopped rampant speculation that Trump will mount a move to either remain in office in 2028, or find a legal workaround to permit a third tilt at the presidency.  Speaking aboard Air Force One, Trump was asked point-blank if he would rule out a third run. "Am I ruling it out? You tell me," he responded. Trump did, however, address one popularly held theory that he could run as Vice President behind JD Vance, with Vance immediately stepping down after winning an election. Despite that too being constitutionally forbidden, Trump said he would not do it because "it's too cute." title: Putin touts the potential of ‚Äòinvincible‚Äô nuclear-capable cruise missile
description: Russian President Vladimir Putin has boasted about the capability of Russia's "invincible" nuclear-capable cruise missile.  The Burevestnik missile, or known by its NATO code-name as "Skyfall", was successfully tested on Sunday, said Putin.  The Russian president appeared in military fatigues to tout the success of his new missile.  During the address, Putin called on his top generals to begin preparing missiles for potential use.  "We need to determine the possible uses and begin preparing the infrastructure for deploying these weapons to our armed forces", Putin said.  Previously, Putin said the weapon is capable of bypassing missile defence systems and has an almost infinite range.  Moscow has boasted of the missile's capability, but it remains unclear if the Burevestnik missile can do what Putin says it can.

description: The near-month-long government shutdown in the United States is affecting air travel.  Safety concerns are rising after airports across the country report major staffing shortages. Since the shutdown began at the start of October, more than 250 Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) facilities have reported staffing problems.

description: US President Donald Trump is headed to Japan after signing a swathe of trade deals with South East Asian nations at the ASEAN summit.
